{"id": "50252", "revid": "283821", "url": "https://baldursgate.fandom.com/wiki?curid=50252", "title": "Tabitha", "text": "Tabitha is a female Lioness controlled by the &lt;a href=\"Beastmaster\"&gt;Beastmaster&lt;/a&gt; in the rear animal pens of the restricted part of the &lt;a href=\"Copper%20Coronet\"&gt;Copper Coronet&lt;/a&gt;. Tabitha is not initially hostile and will not turn hostile unless attacked or when the Beast Master turns hostile, whereupon all the beasts and animals in his area will follow suit.\nTabitha is immune to charm and domination effects. It has a piercing damage attack inflicting 1d10 damage plus strength bonus. It is a non-magical weapon with a speed factor of zero (the fastest possible), with a range of 1, and can attack three times per round.\nMod content.\nThe Beastmaster and Tabitha get a &lt;a href=\"Sword%20Coast%20Stratagems\"&gt;Sword Coast Stratagems&lt;/a&gt; script for a better AI response during combat, should you install the Mod."}
{"id": "34702", "revid": "145657", "url": "https://baldursgate.fandom.com/wiki?curid=34702", "title": "Tablets of Fate", "text": "Tablets of Fate are powerful artifacts in the form of stone slabs that serve to maintain the balance between the forces of Law and Chaos on &lt;a href=\"Toril\"&gt;Toril&lt;/a&gt;. The Tablets also had the additional function of recording the names and purposes of every and primordial in the universe.\nHistory.\nIn the Year of Shadows, 1358 DR, &lt;a href=\"Bane\"&gt;Bane&lt;/a&gt; and &lt;a href=\"Myrkul\"&gt;Myrkul&lt;/a&gt; stole the Tablets from &lt;a href=\"Ao\"&gt;Ao&lt;/a&gt; and hid them in &lt;a href=\"Faer%C3%BBn\"&gt;Faer\u00fbn&lt;/a&gt;. Wrongly suspecting that some of the Overgod's power was derived from these tablets, they hoped to depower and overthrow him. When Ao discovered the Tablets of Fate were missing, he summoned all the deities and asked for those guilty to hand them over. When no one stood forward to admit to stealing the Tablets, Ao cast down all the gods from the heavens, taking their divine power in the process. None of the gods was allowed to return until the tablets were found. Ao tasked &lt;a href=\"Helm\"&gt;Helm&lt;/a&gt; with guarding the Celestial Stairways, which would lead the deities back into their divine realms. For this, he retained his divine powers.\nThe period the gods spent on Toril as mere mortals is known as the &lt;a href=\"Time%20of%20Troubles\"&gt;Time of Troubles&lt;/a&gt;.\nMod content.\nAmong the mortals who helped AO to regain the Tablets were the adventurers Cyric, Midnight, Kelemvor (Lionsbane) and Adon. The first three became gods afterwards, Midnight became a new incarnation of Mystra while Cyric became the god of murder for the slain Bhaal.\nThe hunt for the tablets and the renegade gods can be experienced in a mod extension &lt;a href=\"https%3A//baldursextendedworld.com/Sandrah/\"&gt;Time of Troubles Revisited (ToT)&lt;/a&gt; for the &lt;a href=\"Enhanced%20Edition%20Trilogy\"&gt;Enhanced Edition Trilogy&lt;/a&gt;. The protagonist is converted into one of the adventurers with the others being party members."}
{"id": "51531", "revid": "35642161", "url": "https://baldursgate.fandom.com/wiki?curid=51531", "title": "Tactics Mod", "text": "Weimer's Tactics Mod adds tactical challenges to \".\nStatus.\nThe original mod is not compatible with the \" of the game. However, the following partial +&lt;a href=\"Enhanced%20Edition%20Trilogy\"&gt;EET&lt;/a&gt; ports exist:\nOverview.\nThe Tactics Mod enhances many of the game's existing \"boss\" fights, and adds several new ones.\nThese encounters are meant as tactical combat challenges for experienced players, and add limited roleplaying value.\nTactics enemies tend to have powerful special abilities and immunities, and on top of that their AI likes to \"cheat\" to give them unfair advantages. Beating them requires copious pre-buffing, use of potions, good knowledge of the BG2 spell system \u2013 and for most players, plenty of reloads.\nHow to start the encounters.\n\"(See the README linked in the infobox above.)\"\nExternal links.\n\"(For the mod's main website/forum/download page, see the infobox above.)\""}
{"id": "50329", "revid": "44830706", "url": "https://baldursgate.fandom.com/wiki?curid=50329", "title": "Tactics for BG2EE", "text": "The Tactics for BG2EE mod is a partial -port of Weimer's old &lt;a href=\"Tactics%20Mod\"&gt;Tactics Mod&lt;/a&gt;.\nStatus.\nThis EE port was never completed.\nOverview.\nIt is actually a package that is a macro patch for the original Tactics Modification Pack. For those who never played any of the original Tactics components, the various components add tactical challenge difficulty to in-game encounters, and in some cases add new encounters. As an aside, this early Mod was a major inspiration for the &lt;a href=\"Sword%20Coast%20Stratagems\"&gt;Sword Coast Stratagems&lt;/a&gt; Mod's author.\nComponents Available for Installation:\nSome notes from the Tactics for BG2EE Mod Author (2016):\nObjectives:\nalso modifies some AI scripts to fix the compatibility issues and the\nillogical sections of the code.\nFor more information see the link.\nGallery.\nAs improbable as it may be, this mod faithfully executed running \"The Ritual\" segment of the Tactics mod in BG2EE 2.6.6. It ran perfectly fine alongside &lt;a href=\"Sword%20Coast%20Stratagems\"&gt;SCS&lt;/a&gt; and the &lt;a href=\"Spell%20Revisions\"&gt;Spell Revisions&lt;/a&gt; mods, as well as dozens of other tweaks and quest mods with no noticeable issues or glitches. Below are some screenshots of The Ritual - one of the most absurdly challenging components of the Tactics Mod. It was first created sometime in the 2001-2002 time frame. This mod really taxed my high-level party. The scenario is optionally begun on the Watcher's Keep area map. Speak with Pontifex. The player can accept, decline, or \"think about it\" before deciding what to do the quest and return later if desired."}
{"id": "48360", "revid": "44830706", "url": "https://baldursgate.fandom.com/wiki?curid=48360", "title": "Tad", "text": "Tad is an essential NPC for gaining access to the levels at the &lt;a href=\"Pit%20of%20the%20Faithless\"&gt;bottom of the Pit of the Faithless&lt;/a&gt; during the \"\" campaign. Initially, he seems like any of the other \"Faithful\" from the &lt;a href=\"Cult%20of%20the%20Eyeless\"&gt;Cult of the Unseeing Eye&lt;/a&gt;.\nHowever, he is later found to be a \"traitor\", and \"the only one\" able to grant \"direct\" access to the &lt;a href=\"Beholder%20Hideout\"&gt;Cult's \"god\"&lt;/a&gt; below, for the explicit purpose of &lt;a href=\"Investigate%20and%20Destroy%20the%20Cult%20of%20the%20Eyeless\"&gt;Destroying the Cult of the Eyeless&lt;/a&gt;.\nLocation.\nTad is stationed next to a small circular pit to the southwest of the &lt;a href=\"The%20Old%20Tunnels%23Pit%20of%20the%20Faithless\"&gt;upper part of the Pit of the Faithless&lt;/a&gt; in &lt;a href=\"The%20Old%20Tunnels\"&gt;The Old Tunnels&lt;/a&gt;.\nGameplay.\nTad will speak to the party automatically upon approach:\"Yes, pilgrim?\"When asked \"What is this pit you stand by?\" Tad replies:\"It is the Pit of the Faithless, pilgrim. The unworthy are thrown below to be consumed. Maintain your faith and be strong for the Unseeing Eye.\"He doesn't have much else to say at the moment, until you return from &lt;a href=\"Lower%20Reaches\"&gt;The Lower Reaches&lt;/a&gt; with the &lt;a href=\"Rift%20Device%20Part%20%28first%20part%29\"&gt;Rift Device Part&lt;/a&gt;, and have spoken again to &lt;a href=\"Sassar\"&gt;Sassar&lt;/a&gt;, a Cult Outcast who can be found in the &lt;a href=\"The%20Old%20Tunnels%23Lair%20of%20the%20Cult%20Outcasts%20and%20The%20Lower%20Reaches\"&gt;Inner Chambers&lt;/a&gt; in The Old Tunnels. Sassar tells the party to talk to his friend Tad, while avoiding &lt;a href=\"Gaal\"&gt;Gaal&lt;/a&gt;, in order to gain entry to the levels below the &lt;a href=\"The%20Old%20Tunnels%23Pit%20of%20the%20Faithless\"&gt;Cult Domain&lt;/a&gt;.\nGatekeeper.\nEven though Tad is secretly a Cult traitor, ultimately, he is also the one-and-only gatekeeper to the &lt;a href=\"Pit%20of%20the%20Faithless\"&gt;Bottom of the Pit of the Faithless&lt;/a&gt;, &lt;a href=\"Ghoul%20Town\"&gt;Ghoul Town&lt;/a&gt;, and the &lt;a href=\"Beholder%20Hideout\"&gt;Beholder Hideout&lt;/a&gt;. If you kill him early on, you will not gain access to those areas, and will miss out on much experience and treasure. You can rectify this by using the &lt;a href=\"Console\"&gt;Console&lt;/a&gt; and directly \"move to area\" \"AR0201\". If you are using game platform that does not support the console commands (PS5, Nintendo Switch etc.), then going back to a previous saved game may be the only option.\nSpeaking to Tad with the first &lt;a href=\"Rift%20Device%20Part%20%28first%20part%29\"&gt;Rift Device Part&lt;/a&gt; in inventory, after talking to Sassar, will open up a new dialog option, \"'The eye is blind'?\" that will allow you to question him further.\"You...Sassar sent you? Oh, thank the gods, I am relieved he is still alive! I am Tad...what do you need me to do? You want to enter the beholder's lair? Well... you must go down the Pit of the Faithless. Below is a Secret pathway to the small cave in the lair. I don't know exactly where the passage is. Be wary of the creatures who feed upon the bodies of the faithless that are through down there.\"After Tad opens access, you receive another Journal update:\"I have met Sassar's friend Tad, who has instructed me that I must go down the Pit of the Faithless to reach the pathway that will enter the beholder's treasure niche. The beholder is planning a great mass, soon, so it is unlikely he will be in the niche when I enter. Tad warned of creatures who feed upon the bodies of the faithless who are thrown below, however.\"When the conversation is over, Tad walks off (presumably out of the game for good).\nA stairway icon is now available while hovering over the ledge area that goes out into the center of the smaller pit. Use this to go down into the Pit of the Faithless. The exit is also labeled on the player's map as &lt;a href=\"Investigate%20and%20Destroy%20the%20Cult%20of%20the%20Eyeless%23To%20the%20Lair%20of%20the%20Unseeing%20Eye\"&gt;To the lair of the Unseeing Eye&lt;/a&gt;."}
{"id": "2636", "revid": "47673695", "url": "https://baldursgate.fandom.com/wiki?curid=2636", "title": "Taerom Fuiruim", "text": "Taerom Fuiruim is one of the most skilled and renowned blacksmiths in &lt;a href=\"Faer%C3%BBn\"&gt;Faer\u00fbn&lt;/a&gt;. He can be found at &lt;a href=\"Thunderhammer%20Smithy\"&gt;Thunderhammer Smithy&lt;/a&gt; in Beregost. He sells powerful weapons, the only set of &lt;a href=\"Full%20Plate%20Armor\"&gt;Full Plate Armor&lt;/a&gt; sold in the game and also is willing to craft &lt;a href=\"Ankheg%20Plate%20Mail\"&gt;ankheg plate mail&lt;/a&gt; from &lt;a href=\"Ankheg%20Shell\"&gt;ankheg shell&lt;/a&gt; for a price. He is voiced with an Irish accent.\nTaerom has three apprentices working with him.\nIn &lt;a href=\"Baldur%27s%20Gate%20II\"&gt;Baldur's Gate II&lt;/a&gt;, Taerom is referenced in the description of the &lt;a href=\"Medium%20Shield%20%2B2\"&gt;Medium Shield +2&lt;/a&gt; for sale in &lt;a href=\"Athkatla\"&gt;Athkatla&lt;/a&gt; and &lt;a href=\"Saradush\"&gt;Saradush&lt;/a&gt; as the smith who forged it.\nTaerom refuses to purchase magical jewelry such as amulets and rings as well as wands scrolls and potions."}
{"id": "48438", "revid": "44830706", "url": "https://baldursgate.fandom.com/wiki?curid=48438", "title": "Tagget", "text": "Tagget is a &lt;a href=\"Gnome\"&gt;Gnome&lt;/a&gt; who recently released himself from his &lt;a href=\"Thrall%20Collar\"&gt;Thrall Collar&lt;/a&gt; inside the &lt;a href=\"Planar%20Prison\"&gt;Planar Prison&lt;/a&gt; during the \"\" campaign.\nYou can only meet him during the quest to &lt;a href=\"Rescue%20Raelis%20and%20Haer%27Dalis%20from%20the%20Planar%20Prison\"&gt;Rescue Raelis and Haer'Dalis from the Planar Prison&lt;/a&gt;."}
{"id": "40300", "revid": "44830706", "url": "https://baldursgate.fandom.com/wiki?curid=40300", "title": "Tahazzar", "text": "\"Tahazzar\" is a demon found in &lt;a href=\"Watcher%27s%20Keep%20-%20Tahazzar%20%28AR3012%29\"&gt;Watcher's Keep - Tahazzar (AR3012)&lt;/a&gt; area. \nGameplay.\nTahazzar speaks.\nThis &lt;a href=\"Tanar%27ri\"&gt;Tanar'ri&lt;/a&gt; demon, configured as a sort of &lt;a href=\"Balor\"&gt;Balor&lt;/a&gt; demon will initiate dialogue as soon as the party transitions via a portal into his chamber. \nIf the demon detects that the \"player1\" (usually the protagonist) is a Paladin, or a Cleric, or is of Lawful Good alignment, then hostilities will commence almost immediately when the demon finishes its line:\nIf not, then the demon will say:\nThe party may now select a dialogue reply. If the party wishes it can easily shut down any further exchange by choosing the hostile obvious reply. However, if the party asks about the demon's reference to the \"Blood War\", then more info can be gained, and the demon will give some background about their situation. \nIf the \"player1\" is of Chaotic Good, Neutral Good, or Lawful Neutral &lt;a href=\"Alignment\"&gt;alignment&lt;/a&gt; - just as the demon appears to be asking for some kind of favor or to make a bargain, it'll say:\nAnd hostilities will begin.\nOn the other hand, if \"player1\" isn't good aligned or lawful neutral, Tahazzar will say:\nIf the party declines, then hostilities ensue. Or the party may inquire about any reward, and the demon will say:\nIf the party agrees to do the task, then the player's Journal will receive a new quest entry titled &lt;a href=\"The%20Blood%20War\"&gt;The Blood War&lt;/a&gt;. See that page for further information.\nTahazzar and demons are hostile.\nIf hostilities break out, then expect this Balor to cast several spells, depending on how quickly it is engaged. As long as Tahazzar is still functioning it can cast spells from its scripted arsenal of magic. See the InfoBox for a summary.\nGoing into melee combat with the demon can be hazardous, as it has a modest chance of striking a &lt;a href=\"Kill%20target\"&gt;Kill target&lt;/a&gt; vorpal blow that will destroy the target (if gore is enabled in the player's game options it will \"chunk\" the character's body - no resurrection is possible).\nIf the party's level is at least 16, or if 18, then Tahaaar can create several more tanar'ri allies including &lt;a href=\"Maurezhi\"&gt;Maurezhi&lt;/a&gt; or another &lt;a href=\"Glabrezu%20%28Watcher%27s%20Keep/ToB%29\"&gt;Glabrezu&lt;/a&gt; allies, but not if the player has their game difficulty selection below \"Core\".\nWhen the demon is slain, the party can retrieve two items from its twitching body, one of which is needed to complete the &lt;a href=\"Scepter%20of%20Radiance\"&gt;Scepter of Radiance&lt;/a&gt;. \nNotes.\nIf somehow (it is possible) the party has first encountered &lt;a href=\"Ka%27rashur\"&gt;Ka'rashur&lt;/a&gt; before Tahazzar, then a new dynamic will present in dialogue options. For instance, the party may already possess &lt;a href=\"Ka%27rashur%27s%20Heart\"&gt;Ka'rashur's Heart&lt;/a&gt;. Or the party already made a deal with the &lt;a href=\"Baatezu\"&gt;Baatezu&lt;/a&gt; to obtain Tahazzar's heart, and therefor already has an entry in The Blood War quest. These divergent paths are anticipated and dialogue options to further the story are present in the game.\nMod content.\nThe &lt;a href=\"Sword%20Coast%20Stratagems\"&gt;Sword Coast Stratagems&lt;/a&gt; mod revises Tahazzar, especially with the \"Improved Fiends and Celestials\" component. The demon is now a level 24/24/24 Hit dice creature and casts all spells at those levels. A revised AI script is installed with completely changed smarter and adaptive tactical behavior in combat.\nA revised repertoire of Innate, Wizard and Cleric spells is substituted for use, including: &lt;a href=\"Fire%20Storm\"&gt;Fire Storm&lt;/a&gt;, &lt;a href=\"Breach\"&gt;Breach&lt;/a&gt;, &lt;a href=\"Symbol%2C%20Death%20%28wizard%29\"&gt;Symbol, Death (wizard)&lt;/a&gt;, &lt;a href=\"Symbol%2C%20Stun%20%28wizard%29\"&gt;Symbol, Stun (wizard)&lt;/a&gt;, innate \"Teleport Without Error\", &lt;a href=\"Implosion\"&gt;Implosion&lt;/a&gt;, innate &lt;a href=\"Remove%20Magic\"&gt;Remove Magic&lt;/a&gt;, innate &lt;a href=\"Stoneskin\"&gt;Stoneskin&lt;/a&gt;, and &lt;a href=\"Domination%20%28Innate%29\"&gt;Domination (Innate)&lt;/a&gt;.\nThese spells are \"ForceCast\" and generally aren't interruptible and almost instantly deployed. Some of these spells are cast \"at will\" and are launched when certain targeting criteria are met. Implosion and Firestorm are only useable once per rest.\nAs a Balor, Tahazzar will be wreathed in continuous &lt;a href=\"Aura%20of%20Flaming%20Death\"&gt;Aura of Flaming Death&lt;/a&gt;. Additionally, the demon has two weapons, the vorpal attack slashing flaming sword, and a +5 enchanted flail whip in the shield hand. The whip will strike once per round and can instill some negative status effects. SCS makes these demon attacks respond to weapon proficiency skills, and Tahazzar has five pips in both weapons he wields (similar to a long sword and a flail - think \"Balrog\" from the Lord of the Rings). The end result is more attacks per round, better THAC0 and damage.\nWith the SCS mod, it also changes the \"automatic kill\" dynamic of the demon's vorpal hit, and now allows a saving throw vs. Death at -4 penalty to negate.\nAnd finally, Balors with SCS get a +2-movement modifier as well as additional immunities to several spells, and status effects."}
{"id": "27926", "revid": "44830706", "url": "https://baldursgate.fandom.com/wiki?curid=27926", "title": "Tahazzar's Heart", "text": "Tahazzar's Heart item appears in ' and '.\nGameplay.\nThis is a quest item recovered from the corpse of the demon &lt;a href=\"Tahazzar\"&gt;Tahazzar&lt;/a&gt; in the &lt;a href=\"Watcher%27s%20Keep%20Teleport%20Maze\"&gt;Watcher's Keep Teleport Maze&lt;/a&gt;. \n&lt;a href=\"Ka%27rashur\"&gt;Ka'rashur&lt;/a&gt; demands the heart of a specific &lt;a href=\"Tanar%27ri\"&gt;Tanar'ri&lt;/a&gt;, as part of &lt;a href=\"The%20Blood%20War\"&gt;The Blood War&lt;/a&gt; side quest. "}
{"id": "48740", "revid": "44830706", "url": "https://baldursgate.fandom.com/wiki?curid=48740", "title": "Taibela", "text": "Taibela is a vicious, cannibalistic Halfling &lt;a href=\"Mage\"&gt;Mage&lt;/a&gt; from &lt;a href=\"Athas\"&gt;Athas&lt;/a&gt; who has been abducted along with fellow halflings and now resides within the &lt;a href=\"Inside%20the%20Planar%20Sphere%23The%20Furnace%20Room\"&gt;Furnace Room&lt;/a&gt; inside of the &lt;a href=\"The%20Planar%20Sphere\"&gt;Planar Sphere&lt;/a&gt;.\nThe halfling mage curiously possesses immense physical strength. \nGameplay.\nUpon initiation of hostilities (usually because Taibela has been attacked or detects a party member), the mage has a scripted array of protective buffs that are forced-cast as a group of applied spells (can't be interrupted) including &lt;a href=\"Stoneskin\"&gt;Stoneskin&lt;/a&gt;, &lt;a href=\"Mirror%20Image\"&gt;Mirror Image&lt;/a&gt; and &lt;a href=\"Minor%20Spell%20Turning\"&gt;Minor Spell Turning&lt;/a&gt;.\nAfter this, the mage will attempt offensive damage or disabling spell casting at applicable detected targets and may also Animate Dead for combat support. \nMod content.\nThe &lt;a href=\"Sword%20Coast%20Stratagems\"&gt;Sword Coast Stratagems&lt;/a&gt; mod revises this creature with a new default AI script, and especially with the \"Smarter Mages\" component installed. An entire reworked spell book is memorized, and spell choices are changed as well. The mage is assigned a Conjurer kit now, and more spell casts will naturally be from that school.\nTaibela will open up with a group of (previously cast) protective buffs including: &lt;a href=\"Mirror%20Image\"&gt;Mirror Image&lt;/a&gt;, &lt;a href=\"Shadow%20Door\"&gt;Shadow Door&lt;/a&gt;, &lt;a href=\"Minor%20Globe%20of%20Invulnerability\"&gt;Minor Globe of Invulnerability&lt;/a&gt;, &lt;a href=\"Spell%20Immunity\"&gt;Spell Immunity Divination&lt;/a&gt;, &lt;a href=\"Fireshield%20%28Red%29\"&gt;Fireshield (Red)&lt;/a&gt;, &lt;a href=\"Shield%20%28spell%29\"&gt;Shield (spell)&lt;/a&gt;, &lt;a href=\"Protection%20From%20Normal%20Missiles\"&gt;Protection From Normal Missiles&lt;/a&gt;, &lt;a href=\"Stoneskin\"&gt;Stoneskin&lt;/a&gt; and &lt;a href=\"Non-Detection\"&gt;Non-Detection&lt;/a&gt;.\nWill then attempt to conjure an &lt;a href=\"Invisible%20Stalker\"&gt;Invisible Stalker&lt;/a&gt; for support. After that various options for further offensive and creature summoning spells will be cast, if able, based on the threat assessment scripting.\nThe following will be used and can be instantly released:&lt;br&gt;\nWith the &lt;a href=\"Spell%20Revisions\"&gt;Spell Revisions&lt;/a&gt; mod installed the mage's spells will be the SR version. Instead of Spell Immunity will cast \"\"Dispelling Screen\", and the Fireshield Spell will likely be \"Mesthil's Acid Sheath\"\"."}
