{"id": "12100", "revid": "283602", "url": "https://baldursgate.fandom.com/wiki?curid=12100", "title": "Temple of Lathander (Temple District)", "text": "The Temple of Lathander is a temple in &lt;a href=\"Athkatla\"&gt;Athkatla's&lt;/a&gt; &lt;a href=\"Temple%20District\"&gt;Temple District&lt;/a&gt; during the \"\" campaign.\n&lt;a href=\"Dawnmaster%20Kreel\"&gt;Dawnmaster Kreel&lt;/a&gt; and all the &lt;a href=\"Morning%20Knight\"&gt;Morning Knights&lt;/a&gt; here might be hostile if you sided with the &lt;a href=\"Temple%20of%20Talos%20%28Temple%20District%29\"&gt;Temple of Talos&lt;/a&gt; during the &lt;a href=\"Cleric%20Stronghold\"&gt;Cleric Stronghold&lt;/a&gt; quest. As a consequence, &lt;a href=\"Gorion%27s%20Ward\"&gt;Gorion's Ward&lt;/a&gt; and party will no longer able to trade at the store run by Dawnmaster Kreel.\nMod Gallery.\n "}
{"id": "43603", "revid": "44830706", "url": "https://baldursgate.fandom.com/wiki?curid=43603", "title": "Temple of Lolth", "text": "UNDER CONSTRUCTION\nThe Temple of Lolth is an imposing building in &lt;a href=\"Ust%20Natha\"&gt;Ust Natha&lt;/a&gt; city. It is currently presided over by a high priestess matron mother and handmaidens of Lolth linked to House Despana, the most influential House in Ust Natha.\nUpon entry to the temple, the party's nostrils fill with the slightly acrid and sickly-sweet aroma of strange spices - intermingled with the faint pall of smoldering incense. A barely discernable rhythmic chant can be heard from unknown chambers below.\nThe tall ceilings disappear into the shadows, where black eyes glisten from hundreds of fist-sized spiders above - eerily accompanied by arachnoid chittering and clicks. \nGrotesque and lurid frescoes on the walls depict &lt;a href=\"Drider\"&gt;Driders&lt;/a&gt; on the hunt, and scenes of surfacers being slaughtered. The intricately placed tiles and mosaic floor decor is stunningly detailed.\nGameplay.\nThe temple of Lolth is staffed by various guardians, and one Handmaiden of Lolth. The treasury doors are locked inside, with sentries posted. \nAll interior drow are currently neutral to visitors, and they do not seek out or initiate interaction. Speaking with the various creatures within nets the party mostly polite but stern comments that make it understood that this temple is not a tourist destination, and no funny business is tolerated. Causing any trouble or initiating hostile actions would be foolish.\nUnlike temples on the surface, the temple of Lolth in Ust Natha has no attending cleric to administer temple services.\nIf the party is visiting the temple because Phaere has told you that Matron Mother Ardulace wants to speak with Veldrin, see the note below:\nThe Treasury room.\nSpecial mention to the treasury room is made here. The room cannot be accessed without a special key obtained from Phaere. \nThere are two unique Egg Guard sentries posted at the foot of a small staircase leading to the room. The guards will become hostile if attacked, or if the treasury door is opened with the key. If the treasury door is opened and the guards are then made hostile because of this action, that does not mean the entire temple or city of Ust Natha will also become hostile. These guards can be bypassed with stealth (and left in a hostile state) or even better, slain. \nIntuitively this may seem impossible, as an alarm would be raised, right? Well, no it does not. If the guards are attacked without the key in possession of the party, then the guards will become hostile and trip the city-wide alarm. Also, if for some reason the city alarm has already been triggered, then these guards will be hostile too, just like almost all other drow Ust Natha inhabitants.\nIf entry is made into the treasury chamber, the guards become hostile, and a number of golems are observed within. The golems are not hostile until the container within has been pilfered of the contents - which are the &lt;a href=\"Dragon%20Eggs\"&gt;Dragon Eggs&lt;/a&gt;. Removal will make the golems hostile, and they will attack any detected intruders. If the party wishes to dispose of the golems then they can be fought and destroyed. Alternatively, the party could maintain stealth throughout the pilfering process, say with &lt;a href=\"Sanctuary\"&gt;Sanctuary&lt;/a&gt;, or re-apply &lt;a href=\"Invisibility\"&gt;Invisibility&lt;/a&gt; after the eggs are taken - and then move outside the chamber, close the door behind, and just flee the area. There is more than one way to crack an egg. \nMod content.\nWith the &lt;a href=\"Sword%20Coast%20Stratagems\"&gt;Sword Coast Stratagems&lt;/a&gt; mod all the guards, except the &lt;a href=\"Egg%20Guard\"&gt;Egg Guard&lt;/a&gt; sentries, are assigned smarter AI scripts as well as revised weapon proficiencies and fighting styles commensurate with their class and experience level. The Hand Maiden of Lolth will use appropriate spell buffs if hostilities break out. Note that the \"Seek and Destroy\" scripts given to many golems in the game by SCS aren't used in this Temple, for plot mechanic reasons.\nThe &lt;a href=\"Golem%20Construction%20for%20Spellcasters\"&gt;Golem Construction for Spellcasters&lt;/a&gt; mod makes changes to the guardian golems in the temple treasury. Instead of the ordinary Stone and Clay golems, two are replaced with \"Greater\" Stone and Greater Clay Golems. These new varieties make for a tougher and harder hitting challenge. The Clay golems still use &lt;a href=\"Golem%20Haste\"&gt;Golem Haste&lt;/a&gt;, and the Stone use &lt;a href=\"Golem%20Slow\"&gt;Golem Slow&lt;/a&gt; innate abilities. The mod has some surprising \"On hit\" effects by these golem types not seen in the unmodified game. "}
{"id": "31922", "revid": "31124876", "url": "https://baldursgate.fandom.com/wiki?curid=31922", "title": "Temple of Oghma", "text": "Temples of Oghma can be found in:"}
{"id": "13387", "revid": "44830706", "url": "https://baldursgate.fandom.com/wiki?curid=13387", "title": "Temple of Oghma (Athkatla)", "text": "The only Temple of Oghma in &lt;a href=\"Athkatla\"&gt;Athkatla&lt;/a&gt; is located in the &lt;a href=\"Athkatla%20Docks\"&gt;Athkatla Docks&lt;/a&gt; district.\nThe temple consists of a single room, a small library. The Priest administers the Temple's store and services functions. Donations to the temple can be made through him, curative services negotiated, and potions and other items can be bought. If any items are in the party needing identification, the Priest can do so. \nThe Priest and the Monk of Oghma located within can provide the party with various definitive and more detailed information regarding several topics. This is especially true for a beginning party in Athkatla, and can help fill in some blanks. So, take advantage of the visit and freely ask whatever you can through dialogue. \nSee the Priest and Monk of Oghma pages for details.\nContainers.\nThe bookshelves and the table in the center of the Temple are free to examine for items of use. Taking them will not result in any penalties. There are probably some party members that should perhaps actually look at a book, and not just for the pictures."}
{"id": "46868", "revid": "31124876", "url": "https://baldursgate.fandom.com/wiki?curid=46868", "title": "Temple of Oghma (Baldur's Gate)", "text": "This Temple of Oghma is located in front of the &lt;a href=\"Ducal%20Palace\"&gt;Ducal Palace&lt;/a&gt; and next to &lt;a href=\"Oberan%27s%20Estate\"&gt;Oberan's Estate&lt;/a&gt;. It straddles the dividing line between &lt;a href=\"Central%20Baldur%27s%20Gate\"&gt;central&lt;/a&gt; and &lt;a href=\"North%20Baldur%27s%20Gate\"&gt;north&lt;/a&gt; &lt;a href=\"Baldur%27s%20Gate%20%28city%29\"&gt;Baldur's Gate&lt;/a&gt;. It has no resident &lt;a href=\"Priest%20of%20Oghma%20%28Baldur%27s%20Gate%29\"&gt;priest&lt;/a&gt; present and therefore offers no services."}
{"id": "2092", "revid": "47673695", "url": "https://baldursgate.fandom.com/wiki?curid=2092", "title": "Temple of Oghma (Candlekeep)", "text": "The Temple of Oghma is the only &lt;a href=\"Temples\"&gt;temple&lt;/a&gt; in &lt;a href=\"Candlekeep\"&gt;Candlekeep&lt;/a&gt;. A &lt;a href=\"Priest%20of%20Oghma%20%28Baldur%27s%20Gate%29\"&gt;priest&lt;/a&gt; of &lt;a href=\"Oghma\"&gt;The Lord of Knowledge&lt;/a&gt; offers services here.\nA &lt;a href=\"tutor\"&gt;tutor&lt;/a&gt;, present in this temple of wisdom during the &lt;a href=\"Prologue\"&gt;Prologue&lt;/a&gt;, will explain how the services are used.\nServices.\nThe temple offers the usual services available at all temples found throughout the &lt;a href=\"Sword%20Coast\"&gt;Sword Coast&lt;/a&gt;. Healing and resurrection for bodily health, donations for keeping in good faith with the deities of &lt;a href=\"Faer%C3%BBn\"&gt;Faer\u00fbn&lt;/a&gt;, and &lt;a href=\"Identify\"&gt;identification&lt;/a&gt; of unknown &lt;a href=\"item\"&gt;item&lt;/a&gt;s.\nThe temple also sells the typical healing potions and scrolls sold by all temples, however, it won't be restocked when you return to Candlekeep in &lt;a href=\"Chapter%20Six\"&gt;Chapter Six&lt;/a&gt;.\n&lt;onlyinclude&gt;\nDonate.\n&lt;/onlyinclude&gt;"}
{"id": "45578", "revid": "44830706", "url": "https://baldursgate.fandom.com/wiki?curid=45578", "title": "Temple of Rillifane", "text": "Temple of Rillifane is in &lt;a href=\"Suldanessellar\"&gt;Suldanessellar&lt;/a&gt;. It is where &lt;a href=\"Gorion%27s%20Ward\"&gt;Gorion's Ward&lt;/a&gt; must set the\n&lt;a href=\"Talisman%20of%20Rillifane\"&gt;Talisman of Rillifane&lt;/a&gt;, the &lt;a href=\"Moonblade%20%28Suldanesselar%29\"&gt;moonblade&lt;/a&gt; and the &lt;a href=\"Golden%20Goblet%20of%20Life\"&gt;Golden Goblet of Life&lt;/a&gt; on the altar to summon the &lt;a href=\"Avatar%20of%20Rillifane\"&gt;Avatar of Rillifane&lt;/a&gt;.\nThis area map is cloned and reused as AR2812 for the post Irenicus final battle in the Hine Hells scene with Ellesime.\nGameplay.\nThe party must face a group of &lt;a href=\"Rakshasa\"&gt;Rakshasa&lt;/a&gt; defenders just outside the entry doorway to this temple.\nUpon entry, the temple of the Leaflord Rillifane is seen to be taken over by several of Irenicus's invaders.\nThe male human mage, &lt;a href=\"Suneer\"&gt;Suneer&lt;/a&gt; will make the first move and address the party. A dialogue reply is required, but shortly thereafter, regardless of what is said, Suneer promises to destroy any who would interfere with his master's plans. The enemies attack.\nThe mage will cast a chain of protective buffs, then attempt to cast disabling and or offensive damage spells.\nThe Glabrezu will advance and engage the closest party member it can reach. Likewise for the Iron Golem.\nA raksasha to the east will attempt offensive damage spell casts. Any that engage him in close quarters will be attacked with spells and longsword blows.\nAssuming these creatures are defeated, the party will find no treasures here in the temple. Suneer drops some equipment.\nA central statue with an altar attached to the side is noticeable. It is here that artifacts must be placed in order to awaken the Avatar of Rillifane. If the party doesn't have all of them, then leave the temple and seek out the required missing items and return when they are all in your possession.\nIf all three artifacts are placed on the altar, a series of special effects and a cut scene (CUT54A.bcs) initiates.\nThe avatar is summoned and makes spoken pronouncements. It begins with: \nFor more information see the Avatar of Rillifane page.\nAlso, at the conclusion of this event, the player's Journal will register the following:\nCreatures.\nEnemies.\nThese creatures are in the temple when first entered:\nNPCs.\nThese creatures appear after finishing the final battle with Irenicus in &lt;a href=\"The%20Abyss\"&gt;The Nine Hells&lt;/a&gt; "}
