{"id": "25612", "revid": "52992251", "url": "https://baldursgate.fandom.com/wiki?curid=25612", "title": "Thaldorn Tenhevich", "text": "Thaldorn Tenhevich is one of the leaders of the &lt;a href=\"Iron%20Throne\"&gt;Iron Throne's&lt;/a&gt; operations in the city of &lt;a href=\"Baldur%27s%20Gate%20%28city%29\"&gt;Baldur's Gate&lt;/a&gt;. He is found in a bedroom on the fifth floor of the &lt;a href=\"Iron%20Throne%20Headquarters\"&gt;Iron Throne Headquarters&lt;/a&gt; in &lt;a href=\"South%20Baldur%27s%20Gate\"&gt;South Baldur's Gate&lt;/a&gt;.\nHe can be confronted directly or &lt;a href=\"charmed\"&gt;charmed&lt;/a&gt; to reveal the overall scope of the Iron Throne's plans up to this point. Thaldorn doesn't exhibit much of a spine and it's relatively easy to shake him down for information. When the dialogue ends you can either let him walk or take him out.\nDialogue.\n\"What are you doing here?! Get out of this building before I call the guards.\"\n\"You're here to kill me, aren't you? You can't kill me! Do you know who I am? I'm Thaldorn, one of the leaders of the Iron Throne.\"\n\"Please don't hurt me! You can find everything you need with Rieltar, he's the true leader of the operation. He always carries everything on his person. Am I free to go?\"\n\"The other leaders, Brunos and Rieltar, they're at Candlekeep, attending business with some benefactors from the south. Will you let me go now, please?\"\n\"NOOOOoooooo. Please, please let me live.\"\nor\nShould you choose the dialogue route, the following update will be made in the quest section of your &lt;a href=\"Journal\"&gt;Journal&lt;/a&gt; under the title: Investigating the Iron Throne\nCharmed.\nIf you choose to charm Thaldorn, he'll reveal everything:\nAnd the following update will be made in your Journal under the title: Investigating the Iron Throne"}
{"id": "49775", "revid": "44830706", "url": "https://baldursgate.fandom.com/wiki?curid=49775", "title": "Thalia Thunderburp", "text": "Thalia Thunderburp is the wife of &lt;a href=\"Samuel%20Thunderburp\"&gt;Samuel Thunderburp&lt;/a&gt; and she works as a serving wench in the &lt;a href=\"Five%20Flagons%20Inn\"&gt;Five Flagons Inn&lt;/a&gt;, located in the &lt;a href=\"Bridge%20District\"&gt;Bridge District&lt;/a&gt;. Thalia has some gold in her pockets and a random scroll (with &lt;a href=\"Sword%20Coast%20Stratagems\"&gt;SCS&lt;/a&gt; installed as well. She has a 50% pick pockets skill, so if the party rogue tries to do that to her, there will be a penalty to success.\nShe has extra dialogue if &lt;a href=\"Mazzy\"&gt;Mazzy&lt;/a&gt; speaks with her. Also, a line just for &lt;a href=\"Minsc\"&gt;Minsc&lt;/a&gt; if he initiates the talking."}
{"id": "25634", "revid": "44830706", "url": "https://baldursgate.fandom.com/wiki?curid=25634", "title": "Crimson Death", "text": "Crimson Death is a monster that's usually found in the company of &lt;a href=\"Vampiric%20Mist\"&gt;Vampiric Mist&lt;/a&gt;s, &lt;a href=\"Mist%20Horror\"&gt;Mist Horror&lt;/a&gt;s, and other mist-type monsters. In areas where they are encountered, they usually only appear as a spawned creature, except for the &lt;a href=\"Forest%20of%20Tethir%20%28Shadows%20of%20Amn%29\"&gt;Forest of Tethir&lt;/a&gt; area and inside &lt;a href=\"Coran%27s%20Cabin\"&gt;Coran's Cabin&lt;/a&gt;.\nThey are immune to +1 and non-magical weapons. A 95% magic resistance pretty much makes them immune to any type of &lt;a href=\"Hold%20Monster\"&gt;hold&lt;/a&gt; or &lt;a href=\"Wand%20of%20Paralyzation\"&gt;paralyzation&lt;/a&gt; attempt. They also have complete immunity to cold (including magical cold) and acid \u2014 wands, weapons, or spells. Unlike a Vampiric Mist, they can't naturally see invisible or hidden creatures nor do they inflict any type of level drain upon their victim or gain any type of &lt;a href=\"Hit%20point\"&gt;HP&lt;/a&gt; increase with a successful melee attack. \nA Crimson Death's only weapon is a 3d10 &lt;a href=\"Slashing%20damage\"&gt;Slashing damage&lt;/a&gt; delivered by their elongated tentacle-like appendages."}
{"id": "35384", "revid": "3234315", "url": "https://baldursgate.fandom.com/wiki?curid=35384", "title": "Critical Hit", "text": ""}
{"id": "12773", "revid": "44830706", "url": "https://baldursgate.fandom.com/wiki?curid=12773", "title": "Critical Strike", "text": "Critical Strike is a &lt;a href=\"High-level%20class%20ability\"&gt;High-level class ability&lt;/a&gt; available to &lt;a href=\"Fighter\"&gt;fighters&lt;/a&gt;, &lt;a href=\"Paladin\"&gt;paladins&lt;/a&gt;, &lt;a href=\"Ranger\"&gt;rangers&lt;/a&gt;, and &lt;a href=\"Monk\"&gt;monks&lt;/a&gt;.\nPrerequisite: &lt;a href=\"Power%20Attack\"&gt;Power Attack&lt;/a&gt;.\nRequired for: &lt;a href=\"Smite\"&gt;Smite&lt;/a&gt;.\nGameplay.\nEven if some enemy types are immune to critical hits or backstabbing, this HLA may still be worth activating for guaranteed hits due to the assured 20 roll.\nAny physical attacks during &lt;a href=\"Time%20Stop\"&gt;Time Stop&lt;/a&gt; also automatically land on a target, but it works in a different way - it bypasses the whole to-hit-dodge system."}
{"id": "35305", "revid": "25442597", "url": "https://baldursgate.fandom.com/wiki?curid=35305", "title": "Critical hit", "text": "A critical hit (or crit for short) is an attack that strikes a vital organ and as a result, may do additional damage.\nHow It Works.\nA critical hit occurs when an attack roll results in a 20, before any bonuses are applied. A critical hit will always succeed in striking a target, regardless of the attacking creature's &lt;a href=\"THAC0\"&gt;THAC0&lt;/a&gt; or the target creature's &lt;a href=\"armor%20class\"&gt;armor class&lt;/a&gt;. Critical hits double the damage (including any bonuses) that would otherwise be inflicted . Backstabs can also score critical hits, in which case the total backstab damage will be doubled. When a creature is protected from critical hits, they are protected from the additional damage, not from the hit itself;\u00a0normal damage will still be done.\u00a0 Most helmets offer protection from critical hits.\nCertain conditions can improve the chances of getting a critical hit:"}
{"id": "4576", "revid": "44830706", "url": "https://baldursgate.fandom.com/wiki?curid=4576", "title": "Crom Faeyr", "text": "Crom Faeyr +5\u00a0is a that boosts the wielder's &lt;a href=\"strength\"&gt;strength&lt;/a&gt; to the maximum and instantly slays\u00a0&lt;a href=\"Stone%20Golem\"&gt;Stone Golem&lt;/a&gt;, &lt;a href=\"Clay%20Golem\"&gt;Clay Golem&lt;/a&gt;, &lt;a href=\"Ettin\"&gt;Ettin&lt;/a&gt; and &lt;a href=\"Troll\"&gt;Troll&lt;/a&gt; creatures on a successful hit.\nGameplay.\nThe strength boost applies when wielding it in main or off-hand.\nThe weapon strikes as a +5 enchanted item, inflicting 2d4+3 &lt;a href=\"Crushing%20damage\"&gt;Crushing damage&lt;/a&gt; and +5 &lt;a href=\"Electricity%20damage\"&gt;Electricity damage&lt;/a&gt;. The wielder will also add &lt;a href=\"Strength\"&gt;Strength&lt;/a&gt; modifier damage as well (+14).\nThe electricity damage is non magical and isn't blocked by magic resistance or spell &lt;a href=\"Power%20level\"&gt;Power level&lt;/a&gt; protecions.\nThis is the first obtainable +5 melee weapon that isn't specific to one class (the first being the very restricted &lt;a href=\"Carsomyr\"&gt;Carsomyr&lt;/a&gt;) and thus can hit a mage protected by &lt;a href=\"Improved%20Mantle\"&gt;Improved Mantle&lt;/a&gt;.\nThe weapon is more than the sum of its components, but the components can be equipped by different characters. This is something to consider before running off to Cromwell.\nSee the InfoBox for specific creature types instantly killed by the &lt;a href=\"Slay\"&gt;Slay&lt;/a&gt; effect.\nStrength bonus from weapon considerations.\nThere are &lt;a href=\"Strength%23Equipment\"&gt;a few weapons&lt;/a&gt; that enhance strength and they require some extra consideration: What happens when the weapon is no longer active, because the character switches to a different one? The least obvious is to swap between melee and ranged.\nCarrying ability can be reduced, which could encumber the character. The larger the boost to your natural strength, the bigger the risk of suddenly being encumbered.\nWhile shields remain equipped when using a &lt;a href=\"Sling\"&gt;Sling&lt;/a&gt; or &lt;a href=\"Dart\"&gt;Dart&lt;/a&gt;, off-hand weapons will not.\nAcquisition.\nIn as well as &lt;a href=\"Cromwell\"&gt;Cromwell&lt;/a&gt; in Athkatla will combine the\u00a0&lt;a href=\"Hammer%20of%20Thunderbolts\"&gt;Hammer of Thunderbolts&lt;/a&gt;, &lt;a href=\"Gauntlets%20of%20Ogre%20Power\"&gt;Gauntlets of Ogre Power&lt;/a&gt;, &lt;a href=\"Girdle%20of%20Frost%20Giant%20Strength\"&gt;Girdle of Frost Giant Strength&lt;/a&gt;, and &lt;a href=\"Crom%20Faeyr%20Scroll\"&gt;Crom Faeyr Scroll&lt;/a&gt; for \u00a0to create the hammer.\nIn the game, it can be obtained as a reward of the tier 3-2 battle.\nTrivia.\nThe weapon's required components and its ability to kill the &lt;a href=\"Giants\"&gt;giant-related&lt;/a&gt; &lt;a href=\"ettins\"&gt;ettins&lt;/a&gt; and &lt;a href=\"trolls\"&gt;trolls&lt;/a&gt; on one strike makes this hammer a reference to the &lt;a href=\"w%3Ac%3Aforgottenrealms%3AHammer%20of%20Thunderbolts\"&gt;Hammer of Thunderbolts&lt;/a&gt;, an artifact from multiple editions of \"&lt;a href=\"w%3Ac%3Aforgottenrealms%3ADungeons%20%26amp%3B%20Dragons\"&gt;Dungeons &amp; Dragons&lt;/a&gt;\", which was itself an homage to , the enchanted hammer that is the signature weapon of the god . As Thor canonically inhabited the &lt;a href=\"w%3Ac%3Aforgottenrealms%3AOuter%20Planes\"&gt;Outer Planes&lt;/a&gt; of \"AD&amp;D\", this is a fitting homage.\nAchievements.\nLegendary Relic.\nConstruct Crom Faeyr."}
