{"id": "5952", "revid": "3234315", "url": "https://baldursgate.fandom.com/wiki?curid=5952", "title": "Dealing with the Trademeet genies", "text": "Dealing with the Trademeet genies is a side quest which can be started in &lt;a href=\"Trademeet\"&gt;Trademeet&lt;/a&gt;. Completing this quest makes the genies leave to the delight of the various shop owners.\nAcquisition.\nThis quest can be started independently of the &lt;a href=\"Animal%20trouble%20in%20Trademeet\"&gt;Animal trouble in Trademeet&lt;/a&gt;. &lt;a href=\"High%20Merchant%20Logan%20Coprith\"&gt;High Merchant Logan Coprith&lt;/a&gt; will ask your help in dealing with the \"genie problem\" in Trademeet. They are cornering the market and no other vendor is allowed to make any sales. He directs you to &lt;a href=\"Guildmistress%20Busya\"&gt;Guildmistress Busya&lt;/a&gt; for specifics. You can still talk with the Dao Djinn without speaking with the Mayor and the Guild Mistress, but it makes sense to not do that from a background information standpoint.\nNote.\nIf any member is polymorphed during the celebratory ceremony, then their sculpture at the fountain will show them in this form. This works with the wizard spell &lt;a href=\"Polymorph%20Self\"&gt;Polymorph Self&lt;/a&gt;, as well as with the &lt;a href=\"Druid%23Shapeshifting\"&gt;druidic ability of shapeshifting&lt;/a&gt;. The statue, however, isn't rendered with stony skin, but uses the polymorph creature's usual hide or skin. Additionally, if &lt;a href=\"Wilson\"&gt;Wilson&lt;/a&gt; is in the party his 'statue' just looks like him, no 'petrified' color palette.\nMod content.\nInstalling &lt;a href=\"Afaaq%20the%20Djinni%20Companion\"&gt;Afaaq the Djinni Companion&lt;/a&gt; mod will begin after you defeat the various &lt;a href=\"Rakshasa\"&gt;Rakshasa&lt;/a&gt; and &lt;a href=\"Ihtafeer\"&gt;Ihtafeer&lt;/a&gt;. A teleportation portal will appear on the upper platform inside the cottage. Enter the portal to begin the new quests and adventures offered in the Mod, and potentially gain a seventh party member."}
{"id": "20500", "revid": "978785", "url": "https://baldursgate.fandom.com/wiki?curid=20500", "title": "DeathSpell", "text": ""}
{"id": "5828", "revid": "44830706", "url": "https://baldursgate.fandom.com/wiki?curid=5828", "title": "Death Fog", "text": "Death Fog creates a toxic fog of acid, damaging any creature caught in it, subject to their resistances and immunities. \nSummoned creatures exposed to the fog will be instantly slain.\nGameplay.\nThe caster selects a point on the area map to direct this spell towards and designates this with the targeting cursor.\nAfter the casting is complete a projectile travels to the designated point and rapidly expands into a 30-foot radius cloud of corrosive fog.\nAny creature in the cloud is exposed to 8 &lt;a href=\"Acid%20damage\"&gt;Acid damage&lt;/a&gt; every round remaining within - the cloud lasts 10 rounds (1 Turn).\nThe spell can be blocked by &lt;a href=\"Magic%20resistance\"&gt;Magic resistance&lt;/a&gt; or &lt;a href=\"Spell%20Immunity\"&gt;Spell Immunity: Evocation&lt;/a&gt;.\nThe description is misleading, and \"animal\" life is not a limitation applied to the spell.\nThis spell is not party-friendly, it will destroy your own summoned creatures (unlike the &lt;a href=\"Death%20Spell\"&gt;Death Spell&lt;/a&gt;) and damage your own party members.\nSummoned , &lt;a href=\"Deva\"&gt;devas&lt;/a&gt; and &lt;a href=\"Planetar\"&gt;planetars&lt;/a&gt; are &lt;a href=\"Gate%20%28priest%29\"&gt;gated&lt;/a&gt;/plane shifted and don't count as summoned, thus they don't get destroyed from this spell and simply take the normal damage. &lt;a href=\"Find%20Familiar\"&gt;Familiars&lt;/a&gt; are also not destroyed.\nThe fog can be dispersed with the &lt;a href=\"Zone%20of%20Sweet%20Air\"&gt;Zone of Sweet Air&lt;/a&gt; spell, but a &lt;a href=\"Dispel%20Magic\"&gt;Dispel Magic&lt;/a&gt; effect won't remove it from the battlefield.\nTrivia.\nThe Advanced Dungeons and Dragons 2nd Edition \"Death Fog\" Wizard spell inflicts progressively more damage each round exposed, and the spell cannot be dispersed with a Gust of Wind. The summoned creatures being killed mechanic is not in the pen and paper game version either. See the External links.\nMod content.\n&lt;a href=\"Spell%20Revisions\"&gt;Spell Revisions&lt;/a&gt; mod has changed this arcane spell, revising its title, effects, school and description. See below:\nAcid Fog\nLevel: 6\nSchool: Conjuration\nRange: Long\nDuration: 1 turn\nCasting Time: 6\nArea of Effect: 30\u2019 radius\nSaving Throw: None\nThis spell creates a thick, clinging, greenish cloud. All creatures who aren\u2019t immune to acid suffer 10 points of damage for each round they are exposed to the vapors of the Acid Fog. In addition, due to reduced visibility, creatures inside the cloud move at 50% of their normal rate."}
{"id": "49435", "revid": "47673695", "url": "https://baldursgate.fandom.com/wiki?curid=49435", "title": "Death Gaze", "text": "Death Gaze is an attack spell that's used by the following demonic monsters: &lt;a href=\"Glabrezu%20%28Shadows%20of%20Amn%29\"&gt;Glabrezu&lt;/a&gt;, &lt;a href=\"Master%20of%20Thralls\"&gt;Master of Thralls&lt;/a&gt;, &lt;a href=\"Nabassu\"&gt;Nabassu&lt;/a&gt;, &lt;a href=\"Lea%27liyl\"&gt;Lea'liyl&lt;/a&gt; and &lt;a href=\"Tanar%27ri\"&gt;Tanar'ri&lt;/a&gt;."}
{"id": "18672", "revid": "46775035", "url": "https://baldursgate.fandom.com/wiki?curid=18672", "title": "Death Shade", "text": "Powerful undead creature chasing off the &lt;a href=\"Deck%20of%20Many%20Things\"&gt;Deck of Many Things&lt;/a&gt; users after a possible 3rd draw, Immunity to Turn Undead, can detect invisibility, passive &lt;a href=\"Haste%20effect\"&gt;Weak Haste&lt;/a&gt; effect, disappears once the user is dead."}
{"id": "5817", "revid": "44830706", "url": "https://baldursgate.fandom.com/wiki?curid=5817", "title": "Death Spell", "text": "Death Spell kills instantly all enemy creatures with fewer than 9 Hit Dice and most summoned creatures.\nGameplay.\nThe caster designates a point on the map with the targeting cursor to direct this spell towards.\nWhen the casting is finished a projectile travels to the designated target point and expands to cover a 30-foot radius area with the spell's death effect.\nThe spell works against only enemy creatures, and also enemy creatures whose gender is classified as \"Summoned\".\nEnemy creatures with less than 9 &lt;a href=\"Hit%20Dice\"&gt;Hit Dice&lt;/a&gt; are exposed to a &lt;a href=\"Slay\"&gt;Slay&lt;/a&gt; effect with no saving throw.\n&lt;a href=\"Magic%20resistance\"&gt;Magic resistance&lt;/a&gt; can block the slay effect, as well as &lt;a href=\"Spell%20Immunity\"&gt;Spell Immunity: Necromancy&lt;/a&gt;, and items/spells that protect against instant death can prevent being slain, such as &lt;a href=\"Death%20Ward\"&gt;Death Ward&lt;/a&gt;.\nSummoned enemy creatures (regardless of their hit dice value) in the area of effect are instantly slain (and this can't be blocked by magic resistance or Death Ward).\nNote that summoned enemy creatures such as a , &lt;a href=\"deva\"&gt;deva&lt;/a&gt; or &lt;a href=\"planetar\"&gt;planetar&lt;/a&gt; are &lt;a href=\"Gate%20%28priest%29\"&gt;gated&lt;/a&gt;/plane shifted and are thus immune to this spell. &lt;a href=\"Find%20Familiar\"&gt;Familiars&lt;/a&gt; are not automatically affected and can block it with magic resistance, but their low hit die makes them vulnerable even in Throne of Bhaal. \nThis spell is particularly effective early in , as it is party-friendly AoE spell that can outright kill enemies like and &lt;a href=\"Umber%20Hulk\"&gt;Umber Hulks&lt;/a&gt;.\nKeep in mind that it is also possible to use this spell as a no-save instant kill against enemies with more than 9 hit dice by utilizing level drain effects (such as those inflicted by the spell Energy Drain, the Black Blade of Disaster, Blackrazor, the Totemic Druid's Spirit Wolf summon (level 10+) and so on) so that their level meets the 8 HD threshold.\nTrivia.\nThe Advanced Dungeons and Dragons 2nd Edition \"Death Spell\" doesn't affect other planar creatures, lycanthropes, or the undead. See the External links.\nMod content.\n&lt;a href=\"Spell%20Revisions\"&gt;Spell Revisions&lt;/a&gt; mod has replaced the arcane \"Death Spell\" with \"Banishment\". See below for description:\nBanishment\nLevel: 6\nSchool: Abjuration\nRange: Long\nDuration: Instant\nCasting Time: 6\nArea of Effect: 30\u2019 radius\nSaving Throw: None\nThis spell forces hostile summoned creatures in the area back to their proper plane. Magic resistance does not affect this spell."}
{"id": "46524", "revid": "44830706", "url": "https://baldursgate.fandom.com/wiki?curid=46524", "title": "Death Tyrant", "text": "The \"Death Tyrant\" is a type of &lt;a href=\"beholder\"&gt;beholder&lt;/a&gt; that is more powerful than the ordinary variety, but less so than an &lt;a href=\"Elder%20Orb\"&gt;Elder Orb&lt;/a&gt; or &lt;a href=\"Hive%20Mother\"&gt;Hive Mother&lt;/a&gt;. In the game saga they are not used much - one spawns in &lt;a href=\"Watcher%27s%20Keep%20Final%20Seal\"&gt;Watcher's Keep Final Seal&lt;/a&gt; the fourth time the green button is pressed on the globe machine.\nAnother one appears in a specific stage of the final battle with &lt;a href=\"Amelyssan\"&gt;Amelyssan&lt;/a&gt;, and the Death Tyrant is summoned in to battle the party (MELSUM03.cre), with her shouting \"Come to your mistress, minions of the Abyss!\"\nBackground.\nIn Dungeons and Dragons lore a Death Tyrant is actually a sort of &lt;a href=\"Undead\"&gt;Undead&lt;/a&gt; remnant of a beholder, and this is partially implemented in the game by assigning these creatures an &lt;a href=\"Undead\"&gt;Undead&lt;/a&gt; general designation rather than Monster. Although Undead, the game does not give the creature any of the typical Undead racial or class immunities. It is just a moderately more powerful variety of a standard beholder. The version encountered in the game also has the appearance of an ordinary beholder. Mod content (below) provides a coloration change to the Death Tyrant for differentiation purposes.\nGameplay.\nThe Death Tyrant combat script will target any creature it can detect with various eye stalks, each firing a different beholder blast projectile. The Death Tyrant can see invisible and hidden creatures by script, as long as they are in its visual detection range.\nThe creature launches one to two projectiles each round at a target. The eyestalk ray selection differs from the ordinary beholder, focusing on more direct killing, petrification or wounding attacks. It does not try lightning, fire or charming eye beams. See the list of scripted eye beams in the Info Box.\nThe creature's Cause Wounds beholder blast is the more potent &lt;a href=\"Hive%20Mother\"&gt;Hive Mother&lt;/a&gt; variety (SPIN551.spl), which bypasses magic resistance and has a &lt;a href=\"Power%20level\"&gt;Power level&lt;/a&gt; of 6, so will exceed a &lt;a href=\"Globe%20of%20Invulnerability\"&gt;Globe of Invulnerability&lt;/a&gt; and burn through other spell protections more rapidly. Each beam hit inflicts damage.\nThe creature will also bathe its target with the &lt;a href=\"Anti-Magic%20Ray\"&gt;Anti-Magic Ray&lt;/a&gt; during combat, typically within two rounds.\nMost Death Tyrant beholders are able to cast a single, uninterruptible &lt;a href=\"Death%20Spell\"&gt;Death Spell&lt;/a&gt; upon seeing a summoned creature in range. As such summoned creatures will most likely be banished. Using summoned creatures against a Death Tyrant isn't infeasible but may not be enough to win an encounter on its own. If multiple beholders are present in the same area, they will quickly destroy a group of summoned assailants.\nThe creature has a number of innate immunities as outlined in the InfoBox.\nMod content.\nInstallation of &lt;a href=\"Sword%20Coast%20Stratagems\"&gt;Sword Coast Stratagems&lt;/a&gt; Mod and the \"Tactical Challenges for BG2\" component makes major changes to the Death Tyrant creature. Most of these are covered in the Mod content section of the &lt;a href=\"Beholder\"&gt;Beholder&lt;/a&gt; main article.\nWith this mod, beholders are given different colored animations to distinguish between ordinary beholders, Death Tyrant, &lt;a href=\"Elder%20Orb\"&gt;Elder Orb&lt;/a&gt; and &lt;a href=\"Hive%20Mother\"&gt;Hive Mother&lt;/a&gt; varieties.\nSCS assigns the &lt;a href=\"RING95.ITM\"&gt;RING95.ITM&lt;/a&gt; item to Death Tyrants, as they are classified as &lt;a href=\"Undead\"&gt;Undead&lt;/a&gt;, so they will have all the immunities as most other undead in the game.\nThe Death Tyrant will employ the following beholder rays: &lt;a href=\"Anti-Magic%20Ray\"&gt;Anti-Magic Ray&lt;/a&gt;, Cause Serious Wounds, Disintegrate, Paralyze, Fear, Flesh to Stone, Death Ray (summoned creatures) and Death Ray (other than summoned creatures). The game difficulty selection determines if the Death and Disintegrate eye beams are used. \nDepending on the player's game difficulty setting, typically additional Death Tyrant creatures will be placed with the &lt;a href=\"Unseeing%20Eye\"&gt;Unseeing Eye&lt;/a&gt;, and in the &lt;a href=\"Beholder%20Cave%20in%20Underdark\"&gt;Beholder Cave in Underdark&lt;/a&gt;. They will typically be two or more alongside a &lt;a href=\"Elder%20Orb\"&gt;Elder Orb&lt;/a&gt; and or a &lt;a href=\"Hive%20Mother\"&gt;Hive Mother&lt;/a&gt; in several areas in SoA and ToB. \nNote that with the &lt;a href=\"Spell%20Revisions\"&gt;Spell Revisions&lt;/a&gt; mod, the &lt;a href=\"https%3A//gibberlings3.github.io/SpellRevisions/spells/arcane/level-6/disintegrate\"&gt;Disintegrate&lt;/a&gt; beam will inflict massive &lt;a href=\"Magical%20damage\"&gt;Magical damage&lt;/a&gt; (35d6) with a missed saving throw with -2 penalty, and 5d6 if the save is made. The SR version does not actually process the &lt;a href=\"Disintegrate%20effect\"&gt;Disintegrate effect&lt;/a&gt; however, so the target will not be turned to dust."}
{"id": "5116", "revid": "44830706", "url": "https://baldursgate.fandom.com/wiki?curid=5116", "title": "Death Ward", "text": "Death Ward is a 4th level &lt;a href=\"priest%20spell\"&gt;priest spell&lt;/a&gt;. It protects one creature from all forms of instant death effects.\nGameplay.\n\"Note:\" Death Ward \"does not exist in the &lt;a href=\"Baldur%27s%20Gate%20%28game%29\"&gt;Original BG1&lt;/a&gt;.\"\nSee also.\nOther necessary protection spells from Priests:\nMod content.\n&lt;a href=\"Spell%20Revisions\"&gt;Spell Revisions&lt;/a&gt; mod has changed this Divine spell, revising its range, casting time, and description. See below:\nDeath Ward\nLevel: 4\nSchool: Necromancy\nSphere: Necromantic\nRange: Touch\nDuration: 1 turn/level\nCasting Time: 5\nArea of Effect: 1 creature\nSaving Throw: None\nWhile under the effects of this spell, the recipient is immune to all forms of death magic. This includes, but is not limited to, Death Spell, Disintegrate, Power Word Kill, Finger of Death, and Wail of the Banshee. This effect will last for the duration of the spell or until dispelled."}
{"id": "12777", "revid": "36786428", "url": "https://baldursgate.fandom.com/wiki?curid=12777", "title": "Deathblow", "text": "Deathblow is a &lt;a href=\"High-level%20class%20ability\"&gt;High-level class ability&lt;/a&gt; available to &lt;a href=\"fighter\"&gt;fighter&lt;/a&gt;s, &lt;a href=\"paladin\"&gt;paladin&lt;/a&gt;s, &lt;a href=\"ranger\"&gt;ranger&lt;/a&gt;s, and &lt;a href=\"monk\"&gt;monk&lt;/a&gt;s.\nRequired for: &lt;a href=\"Greater%20Deathblow\"&gt;Greater Deathblow&lt;/a&gt;"}
{"id": "29861", "revid": "3234315", "url": "https://baldursgate.fandom.com/wiki?curid=29861", "title": "Deathbringer", "text": ""}
{"id": "52094", "revid": "44830706", "url": "https://baldursgate.fandom.com/wiki?curid=52094", "title": "Deathbringer Assault", "text": "Deathbringer Assault is an innate passive ability that is \"always on\" available to &lt;a href=\"Sarevok%20Anchev\"&gt;Sarevok Anchev&lt;/a&gt; in the game versions. This ability is linked to Sarevok's &lt;a href=\"deathbringer\"&gt;deathbringer&lt;/a&gt; class. \nThe ability is initiated via the Sarevok creature file internal assigned effect script using &lt;a href=\"Opcode\"&gt;Opcode&lt;/a&gt; 248 \"Set Melee Effect\". Any melee attack that connects with a target has a probability of applying the innate spell effect on that target. Any type of melee attack that hits can initiate the chance to trigger the effects of the ability. This would include a fist attack, dagger thrust or any other melee blow.\nWhen any melee attack successfully hits, there are two different and separate effects that can occur. Both effects will not occur simultaneously. The first is a 10% chance of a &lt;a href=\"Stun\"&gt;Stun&lt;/a&gt;, where the target creature is allowed a save vs. spell with a -4 penalty to negate it. If not, the stun effect has a duration of 2 rounds. It can't be dispelled. A combat screen text message displays \"\"Stunned\" if the save is missed.\nThe other ability has a 3% probability of affecting the target. When that occurs a text message displays on the combat screen indicating \"Deathbringer Assault\"\". The effect applies 200 &lt;a href=\"Slashing%20damage\"&gt;Slashing damage&lt;/a&gt; to the target (regardless of what type of melee weapon hit the target).\nBoth of these effects are not affected by &lt;a href=\"Magic%20resistance\"&gt;Magic resistance&lt;/a&gt;, spell protections such as &lt;a href=\"Globe%20of%20Invulnerability\"&gt;Globe of Invulnerability&lt;/a&gt;, &lt;a href=\"Spell%20Turning\"&gt;Spell Turning&lt;/a&gt;, &lt;a href=\"Spell%20Immunity\"&gt;Spell Immunity&lt;/a&gt; or &lt;a href=\"Spell%20Shield\"&gt;Spell Shield&lt;/a&gt;.\nA &lt;a href=\"Stoneskin\"&gt;Stoneskin&lt;/a&gt; would block the slashing damage, and any sort of slashing damage resistance could mitigate it.\nSome creatures that are designed to be protected against this innate ability (not just the damage that prompts the message \"Deathbringer Assault\", the stun as well) are provided with the &lt;a href=\"SAREVIMM.ITM\"&gt;SAREVIMM.ITM&lt;/a&gt;."}
